94
00:06:07,809 --> 00:06:09,390
Please welcome Stephanie Bayer.

95
00:06:20,634 --> 00:06:20,914
All right.

96
00:06:20,954 --> 00:06:22,615
Time for memes and for me to go fast.

97
00:06:25,297 --> 00:06:26,458
As humans, we all have hearts.

98
00:06:26,658 --> 00:06:28,020
It's just a factor of anatomy.

99
00:06:28,220 --> 00:06:30,321
What we do with those hearts, how we express emotions,

100
00:06:30,381 --> 00:06:32,283
empathy, and feelings is how we begin to differ.

101
00:06:32,823 --> 00:06:36,346
While I enjoy robotic precision and neo-retrofuture aesthetic,

102
00:06:36,406 --> 00:06:38,328
I'm still a human with a heart and must remember,

103
00:06:38,788 --> 00:06:40,109
expressing emotions is OK.

104
00:06:41,652 --> 00:06:44,993
In regards to video games, community management, and player management, that's where things

105
00:06:45,033 --> 00:06:46,273
can get a bit more tricky.

106
00:06:46,774 --> 00:06:49,954
I play with players' hearts every day, and as much as they sometimes tell me they don't

107
00:06:49,974 --> 00:06:51,835
want me to do so, this dance is required.

108
00:06:52,135 --> 00:06:56,036
But, and this is an important but, if you're playing with hearts, you have to be a player

109
00:06:56,316 --> 00:06:56,836
with heart.

110
00:06:58,057 --> 00:07:01,197
Act one, we all have to start somewhere, and that start is the waiting game.

111
00:07:01,337 --> 00:07:05,458
Whether you're building a community or managing an existing community, deciding the tone of

112
00:07:05,518 --> 00:07:09,399
voice, discussion types, and transparency into development must be decided before a

113
00:07:09,459 --> 00:07:10,000
post goes up.

114
00:07:13,104 --> 00:07:15,147
Act two, how do you break through the digital wall?

115
00:07:15,528 --> 00:07:16,749
By listening and reading.

116
00:07:17,050 --> 00:07:19,473
Understanding the audience you're trying to interact with is key.

117
00:07:20,034 --> 00:07:23,339
Even if they are angrily spewing words on a screen, they're there for a reason.

118
00:07:23,359 --> 00:07:27,204
Now to just shape the conversation positively and genuinely.

119
00:07:29,338 --> 00:07:30,459
Act 3, your first post.

120
00:07:30,959 --> 00:07:32,981
This can either mean nothing or mean everything.

121
00:07:33,181 --> 00:07:35,743
It truly depends on the state of your community and what you post.

122
00:07:36,143 --> 00:07:39,526
While main game updates or content releases can be written in the voice of the company,

123
00:07:40,007 --> 00:07:42,329
individual opinions and responses should be in your voice.

124
00:07:42,569 --> 00:07:45,011
It's okay to admit you're an actual human posting on a page.

125
00:07:45,111 --> 00:07:45,831
Humanizing helps.

126
00:07:46,693 --> 00:07:49,514
You're totally thinking, hasn't the internet and jerks screwed this up for us though?

127
00:07:49,854 --> 00:07:53,215
Let's never diminish those who've experienced the ugly side of the internet.

128
00:07:53,475 --> 00:07:57,016
Never pretend harassment on the internet doesn't exist or that people don't suffer because

129
00:07:57,056 --> 00:07:57,236
of it.

130
00:07:57,636 --> 00:08:00,457
But I still believe true connections can be made.

131
00:08:02,117 --> 00:08:03,918
I have hope that we can stand together.

132
00:08:04,078 --> 00:08:04,798
We can unite.

133
00:08:05,218 --> 00:08:09,039
Finding commonality in simple things can be powerful, such as the explosive pineapple

134
00:08:09,099 --> 00:08:09,839
on pizza debate.

135
00:08:10,219 --> 00:08:14,020
While it may seem trivial, it does prove the point that finding community can be as easy

136
00:08:14,080 --> 00:08:16,081
as agreeing or disagreeing on a pizza topping.

137
00:08:17,580 --> 00:08:20,962
Approaching an audience with a sense of heart means staying cool and balanced, addressing

138
00:08:21,022 --> 00:08:24,404
negative issues swiftly while still highlighting the good things in the community all at once.

139
00:08:24,925 --> 00:08:26,125
But still you wonder, how?

140
00:08:26,566 --> 00:08:29,067
How can everyone partake in the empathy game successfully?

141
00:08:33,650 --> 00:08:35,431
Some are gifted with emotional intelligence.

142
00:08:35,651 --> 00:08:36,491
Most have to learn it.

143
00:08:36,712 --> 00:08:38,913
Empathy is a skill that becomes better with practice.

144
00:08:39,473 --> 00:08:41,895
Though you're still dealing with the changing landscape of human emotion.

145
00:08:42,953 --> 00:08:44,153
No striving for perfection.

146
00:08:44,434 --> 00:08:48,495
Practice what you can, like active listening, micro expressions, and tone can help make

147
00:08:48,515 --> 00:08:50,156
you a more heart forward communicator.

148
00:08:51,057 --> 00:08:51,837
You're doing posts.

149
00:08:51,917 --> 00:08:52,337
Now what?

150
00:08:52,917 --> 00:08:54,998
Do spend more in depth time with your biggest supporters.

151
00:08:55,118 --> 00:08:57,700
Don't stretch yourself too thin communicating on all platforms.

152
00:08:58,060 --> 00:08:59,641
Do realize you can only do so much.

153
00:08:59,981 --> 00:09:01,501
Don't try to own every conversation.

154
00:09:01,641 --> 00:09:04,443
Be honest and let the community know you still deserve down time.

155
00:09:05,725 --> 00:09:06,805
Still too much negativity?

156
00:09:07,145 --> 00:09:10,386
I could spend lots of time on this topic, but here's my shortest version possible.

157
00:09:10,806 --> 00:09:12,826
I run communities on a two-strike rule.

158
00:09:12,906 --> 00:09:15,847
First offense, call them out and request respectful communication.

159
00:09:16,167 --> 00:09:17,848
If they still go ham, remove them.

160
00:09:18,208 --> 00:09:19,528
Don't be afraid to tell them to go.

161
00:09:19,668 --> 00:09:21,429
If their goal is to troll, you don't need them.

162
00:09:22,629 --> 00:09:23,849
Feel like you don't know what you're doing?

163
00:09:24,189 --> 00:09:25,750
Hesitation is normal in the beginning.

164
00:09:25,770 --> 00:09:28,070
If a reaction is negative, don't beat yourself up.

165
00:09:28,190 --> 00:09:30,651
Just spend time figuring out where your message is going wrong.

166
00:09:31,011 --> 00:09:31,651
Is it content?

167
00:09:31,891 --> 00:09:32,311
Delivery?

168
00:09:32,491 --> 00:09:32,791
Tone?

169
00:09:33,251 --> 00:09:33,832
Don't give up.

170
00:09:37,508 --> 00:09:41,370
When your audience goes negative, in most cases a faux pas post can be fixed.

171
00:09:41,711 --> 00:09:43,732
So take a breath and then get ready to work again.

172
00:09:44,112 --> 00:09:45,673
Go back to Act 2, reading.

173
00:09:46,114 --> 00:09:47,975
Read the complaints, read between the lines.

174
00:09:48,175 --> 00:09:49,596
Really try to absorb the issue.

175
00:09:49,836 --> 00:09:52,138
Stay open-minded, don't get defensive.

176
00:09:53,745 --> 00:09:56,448
Pro tip, pick a loud dissenter and a loud supporter

177
00:09:56,508 --> 00:09:57,790
and have a Google Hangout with them.

178
00:09:58,250 --> 00:10:00,453
Really listen to what they have to say, good and bad.

179
00:10:00,813 --> 00:10:02,335
Don't allow yourself to be abused, though.

180
00:10:02,455 --> 00:10:03,917
If they can't behave, end the Hangout.

181
00:10:04,277 --> 00:10:05,639
Take notes during the conversation.

182
00:10:05,759 --> 00:10:07,541
Create an actionable item list from it.

183
00:10:09,802 --> 00:10:11,985
Sometimes you have to apologize for the hearts you've broken.

184
00:10:12,305 --> 00:10:16,109
If you've truly listened to the community and a mistake was yours, sincerely apologize

185
00:10:16,149 --> 00:10:16,810
and move forward.

186
00:10:16,830 --> 00:10:20,794
If a direct apology is unnecessary, create a post that displays an understanding of the

187
00:10:20,814 --> 00:10:21,635
community's feelings.

188
00:10:21,916 --> 00:10:25,339
Directly acknowledging them is key to regaining trust and making amends.

189
00:10:26,599 --> 00:10:30,021
Once an apology recognition post is posted, get back to business as usual.

190
00:10:30,182 --> 00:10:31,883
Remind players of positive stuff coming up.

191
00:10:32,243 --> 00:10:35,345
Feel free to highlight an in-joke in a post to show them that you're still reading what

192
00:10:35,385 --> 00:10:35,885
they're saying.

193
00:10:36,406 --> 00:10:39,248
Use digital icebreakers or pop culture posts to get them talking again.

194
00:10:39,548 --> 00:10:41,029
It may seem cheesy, but it works.

195
00:10:42,264 --> 00:10:44,447
Here are two ways I went hard forward at work.

196
00:10:44,947 --> 00:10:49,373
Innocuous contest posts I did led me to chatting with a cancer patient who I ended up bringing

197
00:10:49,413 --> 00:10:50,675
into the studio to meet the team.

198
00:10:51,336 --> 00:10:55,221
I reached out to the angriest grandma ever on Facebook and she ended up becoming a weekly

199
00:10:55,301 --> 00:10:56,643
tournament runner for our game.

200
00:10:58,244 --> 00:11:00,406
What can be gained by playing with hearts or sharing your heart?

201
00:11:00,606 --> 00:11:04,070
You can gain different perspectives on how players interact with your content, as well

202
00:11:04,130 --> 00:11:06,092
as a reminder that players are people too.

203
00:11:07,393 --> 00:11:10,376
98% of your players just want to have fun and have their joy tank filled while you're

204
00:11:10,396 --> 00:11:11,137
playing your game.

205
00:11:11,557 --> 00:11:13,159
You make content that touches hearts.

206
00:11:14,633 --> 00:11:16,915
In summation, playing with hearts is tricky but worthwhile.

207
00:11:17,435 --> 00:11:18,956
It's okay to help make people happy.

208
00:11:19,117 --> 00:11:21,098
It's okay to find joy in making others happy.

209
00:11:21,298 --> 00:11:23,200
It's okay to play with hearts as long as you're willing

210
00:11:23,220 --> 00:11:24,121
to share your heart as well.

211
00:11:24,561 --> 00:11:25,982
It may be scary or make you nervous,

212
00:11:26,243 --> 00:11:27,704
but hearts and passion are what build

213
00:11:27,724 --> 00:11:29,285
successful long-term communities.

214
00:11:30,391 --> 00:11:33,933
While not trying to promote unhealthy habits, if you ever speak to a community manager and

215
00:11:33,953 --> 00:11:37,174
they talk about drinking a lot, that's because the toll on their heart is sometimes quite

216
00:11:37,214 --> 00:11:37,434
great.

217
00:11:37,454 --> 00:11:40,996
If you see your community manager looking down, don't hesitate to ask them what's up,

218
00:11:41,396 --> 00:11:43,237
offer a cup of coffee or even just say thanks.

219
00:11:43,677 --> 00:11:45,718
This small gesture does wonders for the heart.

220
00:11:46,718 --> 00:11:46,978
Thank you.

221
