And UX design is a relatively new field and what user experience designers do is advocate

225
00:12:26,313 --> 00:12:30,619
for users while ensuring that business goals are met by making sure that technology is

226
00:12:30,679 --> 00:12:31,140
reliable.

227
00:12:32,045 --> 00:12:36,649
So in terms of games, UX designers ensure that games interfaces are intuitive and that

228
00:12:36,929 --> 00:12:40,852
games are challenging while also making sure that they're not frustrating enough to quit.

229
00:12:41,393 --> 00:12:45,657
And game development studios are noticing and starting to hire them, which is awesome.

230
00:12:46,698 --> 00:12:51,482
So it's very easy to think that one must be an expert to know how to create a seamless,

231
00:12:51,582 --> 00:12:52,983
intuitive, engaging game.

232
00:12:53,403 --> 00:12:56,706
But you don't have to be an expert to think about UX design, and it's actually important

233
00:12:56,746 --> 00:12:59,208
that everyone on the team is thinking about it.

234
00:13:02,816 --> 00:13:08,319
So here are several tricks, four in total, to start thinking about UX design. And these are

235
00:13:08,339 --> 00:13:13,061
things that game development studios, whether you're a million people or one person can use

236
00:13:13,301 --> 00:13:18,904
to make your games more usable and therefore immersive if that's your cup of tea. Trick

237
00:13:18,924 --> 00:13:23,967
number one, arts and crafts. So UX designers are known to carry around a toolkit of like

238
00:13:24,047 --> 00:13:27,808
dollar store stuff, including things like pens, paper, sticky notes, et cetera.

239
00:13:28,196 --> 00:13:32,170
Because we basically never left kindergarten and it helps us to work better in the long term.

240
00:13:34,479 --> 00:13:39,181
So firstly I usually start by drawing a user flow diagram and that can be on paper or

241
00:13:39,301 --> 00:13:43,022
digitally and this helps me to figure out logic before I get too far into the

242
00:13:43,222 --> 00:13:47,184
programming process so I'm not building anything yet. So I can actually start focusing

243
00:13:47,244 --> 00:13:52,646
on systems design before I've started prototyping or programming. I also then proceed

244
00:13:52,706 --> 00:13:58,068
into drawing those different states by fleshing things out again on paper so that I can

245
00:13:58,108 --> 00:14:00,929
visually explain my idea without getting too far again.

246
00:14:01,469 --> 00:14:05,213
So you can find that your ideas come out better when you're not preoccupied with the code

247
00:14:05,413 --> 00:14:06,354
or how things look.

248
00:14:07,195 --> 00:14:11,419
And all of this requires just three shapes which are circles, squares and triangles.

249
00:14:12,040 --> 00:14:16,104
And I just want to like really point out that you don't have to be an artist to be a UX

250
00:14:16,124 --> 00:14:20,268
designer or do UX design because we're not making things pretty, we're figuring out systems.

251
00:14:23,300 --> 00:14:27,684
So trick number two is compassion. And I use this word because empathy is a bit of a buzz

252
00:14:27,704 --> 00:14:33,308
word right now. And I just want to note what the definition of that is. It's the feeling that

253
00:14:33,348 --> 00:14:38,211
arises when you are confronted with another suffering and you want to actually relieve

254
00:14:38,231 --> 00:14:43,515
that suffering. So in 2017, people are much less tolerant regarding things that take up

255
00:14:43,555 --> 00:14:47,498
their time. So you want to make sure that you're considering their emotions when you're

256
00:14:47,518 --> 00:14:48,518
making design choices.

257
00:14:48,959 --> 00:14:52,820
So figure out ways to keep people engaged without relying on tropes that cause frustration

258
00:14:53,220 --> 00:14:54,101
like grinding.

259
00:14:55,141 --> 00:15:00,943
And you want to also make your game worth playing by ensuring that every piece of complexity

260
00:15:01,003 --> 00:15:04,264
that you're putting into your game is weighed against the value that it provides.

261
00:15:05,064 --> 00:15:09,005
So usually what UX designers do is prioritize the most important features and either de-scope

262
00:15:09,045 --> 00:15:10,666
or completely cut out ones that don't matter.

263
00:15:11,727 --> 00:15:15,988
Trick number three is research, which happens at every point of the design process.

264
00:15:16,508 --> 00:15:19,728
Because we all make assumptions, and it's really important to kill those assumptions

265
00:15:20,269 --> 00:15:23,009
before they tank your project, basically.

266
00:15:23,029 --> 00:15:26,630
So I'm going to talk about three that I rely on as a designer who makes games.

267
00:15:27,310 --> 00:15:30,191
The first of which is doing competitive analyses.

268
00:15:30,291 --> 00:15:35,032
So I make sure that I understand the competitive space before creating solutions by asking

269
00:15:35,052 --> 00:15:36,472
things like, who's doing a great job?

270
00:15:36,792 --> 00:15:38,033
Where's there space for improvement?

271
00:15:38,133 --> 00:15:39,373
And how is our project different?

272
00:15:39,513 --> 00:15:41,513
And this helps to provide a great direction for us.

273
00:15:42,975 --> 00:15:49,805
Then I do interviews. So I talk to perspective players and I again use that to help me kind of

274
00:15:49,845 --> 00:15:53,711
kill my assumptions by asking questions like what kinds of games do you play? Can you

275
00:15:53,751 --> 00:15:57,937
recall a time that you quit playing a game and why? Or just watching them play games like mine.

276
00:15:59,109 --> 00:16:04,035
And then I get to testing. So once you actually have something built, you can start to test

277
00:16:04,075 --> 00:16:09,082
your ideas. And by testing those solutions, you can get data that helps to back the

278
00:16:09,102 --> 00:16:13,108
solution that you actually go with in the final version. And you keep testing until the

279
00:16:13,148 --> 00:16:14,950
product feels good enough to launch.

280
00:16:16,507 --> 00:16:20,928
And then trick number four is sharing. So one of the biggest things that I do as a user

281
00:16:20,948 --> 00:16:25,270
experience designer is kill the secrecy because people love to be in their own corners doing

282
00:16:25,290 --> 00:16:31,612
their own thing without sharing stuff with each other. But UX is all about transparency. So

283
00:16:32,232 --> 00:16:36,754
user experience designers talk to their team very often. They share learnings and work to

284
00:16:36,794 --> 00:16:42,456
ensure that everyone is on the same page. And this helps to let people communicate better and

285
00:16:42,576 --> 00:16:45,957
work better and deliver work much faster than they would otherwise.

286
00:16:47,870 --> 00:16:52,831
Next it also helps you to get more feedback which is great because everyone thinks

287
00:16:52,912 --> 00:16:57,513
differently and you want to make sure that you're figuring out who your audience is and

288
00:16:57,553 --> 00:17:01,074
that feedback can really help you because some of it's not going to be that great to be

289
00:17:01,094 --> 00:17:06,116
honest. Some of it's going to be terrible. And then finally it also helps you to get more

290
00:17:06,156 --> 00:17:09,958
attention by sharing your progress with the public for example. You can actually get

291
00:17:09,998 --> 00:17:14,759
people excited before they actually see the game or actually play it in real life and you

292
00:17:14,779 --> 00:17:15,900
can actually use that for feedback.

293
00:17:18,970 --> 00:17:22,573
So that's everything I wanted to cover in this very quick talk. I hope this helps you

294
00:17:22,593 --> 00:17:26,596
understand a little bit about what I and other UX designers do every day because every game

295
00:17:26,637 --> 00:17:30,800
I've made has benefited from my work as a designer and I'm really excited to see us all

296
00:17:30,860 --> 00:17:35,243
making better, more usable games. So thank you so much and have a great rest of your

297
00:17:35,283 --> 00:17:36,064
conference. Yay!

298
00:17:36,084 --> 00:17:36,264
Thank you.

