00:18:05,037 --> 00:18:08,438
but take a photo if the subject interests you, or watch it in the poll.

305
00:18:11,729 --> 00:18:13,369
Have you ever read A Good Car Chase?

306
00:18:14,010 --> 00:18:15,770
I can't recall where I first heard this question,

307
00:18:16,210 --> 00:18:18,470
but I do remember having more fingers than examples.

308
00:18:19,211 --> 00:18:20,611
I know the question is reductive,

309
00:18:20,671 --> 00:18:22,391
behind it is the idea that every medium

310
00:18:22,431 --> 00:18:24,492
has its own particular expressive power.

311
00:18:28,332 --> 00:18:29,653
Books communicate with language,

312
00:18:30,033 --> 00:18:31,413
film through visual montage,

313
00:18:31,893 --> 00:18:33,453
music through non-linguistic sound.

314
00:18:34,173 --> 00:18:35,714
So when we consume a piece of media,

315
00:18:35,894 --> 00:18:38,134
its form acts as a filter for the kind of meaning

316
00:18:38,154 --> 00:18:40,815
we can derive from it, even when the content is similar.

317
00:18:45,317 --> 00:18:49,099
Modern video games complicate this filter by scrambling existing forms together.

318
00:18:49,279 --> 00:18:52,100
They are a multi-medium, often with no fixed source of meaning.

319
00:18:52,580 --> 00:18:56,182
Some games are novelistic, some are cinematic, while others flout all conventions.

320
00:18:56,562 --> 00:18:58,824
But most games do have a common formal quality.

321
00:19:01,905 --> 00:19:06,688
Because of their interactive nature, games are singular in that they communicate meaning through dynamic systems.

322
00:19:07,148 --> 00:19:10,410
And by interacting with these systems, players can learn how to recognize them,

323
00:19:10,630 --> 00:19:12,951
how to think about them, and how to change them if need be.

324
00:19:18,939 --> 00:19:21,462
We can call this heightened awareness systems literacy.

325
00:19:21,902 --> 00:19:24,545
Just as we talk about musical literacy, or visual literacy,

326
00:19:24,645 --> 00:19:26,868
or language literacy, systems literacy

327
00:19:26,948 --> 00:19:28,590
is a description of a person's ability

328
00:19:28,870 --> 00:19:31,173
to think abstractly about dynamic systems.

329
00:19:32,594 --> 00:19:32,815
Click.

330
00:19:35,914 --> 00:19:40,299
In real life, the political and economic and social systems that influence our behavior

331
00:19:40,359 --> 00:19:43,042
can be vast, vague, and almost invisible to us.

332
00:19:43,542 --> 00:19:47,547
And when they break down or fail us in some way, we don't always comprehend the scope

333
00:19:47,867 --> 00:19:48,888
or the shape of the problem.

334
00:19:49,429 --> 00:19:50,029
For example...

335
00:19:51,967 --> 00:19:57,569
In the 1960s, French sociologist Maurice Duvorger observed that two-party political systems

336
00:19:57,629 --> 00:20:01,770
were often an emergent property of win-and-take-all elections in single-seat districts.

337
00:20:02,190 --> 00:20:05,692
In other words, America's voting system has created its two parties.

338
00:20:07,833 --> 00:20:12,034
Political scientists know this statistical effect, but there is little mainstream discussion

339
00:20:12,074 --> 00:20:16,856
of it, resulting in those who argue that strengthening third parties in the USA is only a matter

340
00:20:16,876 --> 00:20:17,816
of voter willpower.

341
00:20:18,217 --> 00:20:20,517
If we only voted our conscience, then we could fix it.

342
00:20:24,431 --> 00:20:28,833
But this is wrong. To produce real change, we'll need to amend our voting laws in ways

343
00:20:28,873 --> 00:20:33,475
that foster multiple parties. Unfortunately, this level of abstract thinking doesn't come

344
00:20:33,516 --> 00:20:37,377
naturally to many people, but a well-designed game could make this abundantly clear.

345
00:20:37,397 --> 00:20:41,560
And that's a great website if you want to see it. Oops.

346
00:20:43,233 --> 00:20:46,734
Desire paths are another common example of a lack of systems literacy.

347
00:20:46,874 --> 00:20:48,474
We've all seen situations like this.

348
00:20:49,055 --> 00:20:52,656
Desire paths occur when the system we design does not adequately serve the needs of the

349
00:20:52,676 --> 00:20:53,376
people using it.

350
00:20:53,916 --> 00:20:55,656
But this failure can be instructive.

351
00:20:57,217 --> 00:21:00,858
When we have a direct experience with dynamic systems, we can think more clearly about how

352
00:21:00,878 --> 00:21:02,619
they affect us and how we can affect them.

353
00:21:03,039 --> 00:21:04,359
This is Michigan University.

354
00:21:04,779 --> 00:21:08,480
All the walkways on this campus began as desire paths that were later paved over.

355
00:21:11,265 --> 00:21:13,887
As game developers, we're all familiar with this process.

356
00:21:14,287 --> 00:21:16,989
We design, we experiment, we test, we redesign.

357
00:21:17,430 --> 00:21:20,592
And at the end of this process, if we've been vigilant, we haven't just made a game,

358
00:21:21,012 --> 00:21:24,455
we've built a small system that can tell our players something true about the world.

359
00:21:26,816 --> 00:21:30,239
Games are good at teaching large-scale systems in meaningful ways.

360
00:21:30,779 --> 00:21:34,842
When I play Pandemic, I don't just learn about exponential disease propagation,

361
00:21:35,162 --> 00:21:35,863
I manipulate it.

362
00:21:36,263 --> 00:21:40,486
And when I play Twilight Struggle, I participate in a zero-sum Cold War conflict.

363
00:21:42,852 --> 00:21:46,415
What thrills me about our industry is that we can take this process much further.

364
00:21:46,955 --> 00:21:55,222
We can explore political, economic, and social systems, combine them, and infuse them with empathy and style in a way that poses difficult questions.

365
00:21:57,604 --> 00:22:01,607
Does Bioshock's gameplay critique Randian objectivism or miss the point entirely?

366
00:22:01,987 --> 00:22:05,170
How does Fallout 4's survival mode fundamentally alter a player's behavior?

367
00:22:05,470 --> 00:22:07,992
Does Spore champion evolution or creationism?

368
00:22:08,352 --> 00:22:10,594
Should Bungie have gotten rid of Destiny's loot cave?

369
00:22:12,923 --> 00:22:17,246
As a novel, Papers, Please might have been one of a thousand moderately interesting Cold War stories,

370
00:22:17,587 --> 00:22:21,589
but as a game, players participate directly in an indifferent bureaucracy,

371
00:22:21,750 --> 00:22:24,752
which on its surface seems a model of efficient protocol.

372
00:22:27,574 --> 00:22:32,097
As a film, This War of Mine might have won an Oscar for best set design and costume design,

373
00:22:32,677 --> 00:22:37,901
but as a game, it implicates its audience in the daily struggle to balance an individual's need to survive

374
00:22:38,381 --> 00:22:41,023
against his or her desire for trust and community.

375
00:22:42,644 --> 00:22:46,627
I recently played this wonderfully infuriating game to build a better mouse trap.

376
00:22:47,008 --> 00:22:52,633
It's a very sober look at the near impossibility of treating laborers humanely in an economic

377
00:22:52,693 --> 00:22:56,497
system that prioritizes constant economic growth.

378
00:22:59,509 --> 00:23:03,350
This is only a sample of course. Consider all the subjects that would be best served

379
00:23:03,410 --> 00:23:09,312
not by a story but through a dynamic system. Evolution, climate change, institutional racism,

380
00:23:09,713 --> 00:23:13,794
the war on drugs, mental health issues, even subprime mortgage lending.

381
00:23:17,268 --> 00:23:19,251
Unfortunately, we do live in interesting times.

382
00:23:19,471 --> 00:23:21,594
Interesting and increasingly complicated times.

383
00:23:21,954 --> 00:23:24,257
But this complication can be upset by the work that we do.

384
00:23:24,598 --> 00:23:26,420
Through systems literacy, we can teach players

385
00:23:26,460 --> 00:23:29,184
how to navigate a world full of intricate and dynamic systems

386
00:23:29,444 --> 00:23:31,447
that are guiding us, whether we know it or not,

387
00:23:31,688 --> 00:23:32,348
into the future.

388
00:23:32,969 --> 00:23:33,170
