546
00:33:01,855 --> 00:33:05,718
who will just dominate a conversation if you let him. And later on he'll just straight up talk

547
00:33:05,938 --> 00:33:11,443
over you without even giving you time to interject. But if you're silent all the time,

548
00:33:11,483 --> 00:33:15,567
that's suspicious. He thinks it's weird that you're being so quiet. So in conversations with

549
00:33:15,607 --> 00:33:18,589
him, you can't be defensive. You don't want to fly up half cocked. But if you don't say

550
00:33:18,789 --> 00:33:22,873
something, you'll never even manage to get an award in edgewise. The player feels like they

551
00:33:22,933 --> 00:33:24,875
have to be aggressive while talking with him.

552
00:33:27,029 --> 00:33:30,330
However, in other situations, silence can be a meaningful choice too.

553
00:33:30,790 --> 00:33:35,171
If you're quiet in a romantic one-on-one conversation, the person you're talking to will acknowledge

554
00:33:35,211 --> 00:33:35,371
that.

555
00:33:35,971 --> 00:33:38,552
Often it's even treated as a specific statement.

556
00:33:42,633 --> 00:33:44,153
Sometimes it conveys uncertainty.

557
00:33:44,753 --> 00:33:47,294
Other times it conveys a trust to let the other person take charge.

558
00:33:47,834 --> 00:33:52,175
It depends on the context and it depends on when the choices appear at all.

559
00:33:58,807 --> 00:34:02,469
Or you can have someone who asks you questions one-on-one all the time and that comes across

560
00:34:02,529 --> 00:34:03,550
as being very needy.

561
00:34:04,130 --> 00:34:06,752
Suddenly it's a lot more meaningful if only one person does that.

562
00:34:07,493 --> 00:34:11,055
All these different types of interaction pacings tell you different things about the character

563
00:34:11,075 --> 00:34:11,856
that you're talking to.

564
00:34:14,411 --> 00:34:16,832
The whole reason why you have these rules is to break them.

565
00:34:17,312 --> 00:34:20,834
Think of the structures you're creating as a toolbox for evoking emotions.

566
00:34:21,414 --> 00:34:23,635
If you set up the player to expect things to go a certain way,

567
00:34:24,015 --> 00:34:25,576
then you undermine that expectation.

568
00:34:25,636 --> 00:34:26,497
It'll stand out more.

569
00:34:26,677 --> 00:34:27,597
It'll have dramatic effect.

570
00:34:28,077 --> 00:34:29,018
Maybe it can even be funny.

571
00:34:30,578 --> 00:34:32,139
All this applies on a larger scale, too.

572
00:34:32,739 --> 00:34:35,781
We build conversations out of choices, build scenes out of conversations,

573
00:34:35,841 --> 00:34:37,201
and build character arcs out of scenes.

574
00:34:37,642 --> 00:34:38,942
I'm not going to go into detail about this,

575
00:34:38,962 --> 00:34:41,724
but everything I've said about pacing applies to these larger units, too.

576
00:34:42,184 --> 00:34:44,005
But the base unit is the interaction.

577
00:34:46,426 --> 00:34:49,247
That is to say, the story itself is built out of interactions.

578
00:34:49,727 --> 00:34:51,727
And everything that you present to the player

579
00:34:51,787 --> 00:34:53,587
is just there to bring them to the next interaction.

580
00:34:54,068 --> 00:34:55,928
By pacing things in an expected way,

581
00:34:55,948 --> 00:34:57,888
they'll anticipate and look forward

582
00:34:57,928 --> 00:34:59,729
to the next time they get to provide input.

583
00:35:02,489 --> 00:35:05,050
Let the player feel involved because their anticipation

584
00:35:05,190 --> 00:35:06,810
matches the protagonist's anticipation

585
00:35:06,830 --> 00:35:07,570
of providing input.

586
00:35:08,151 --> 00:35:09,811
All those interactions, all those things

587
00:35:09,831 --> 00:35:11,271
that the player anticipates, that's

588
00:35:11,291 --> 00:35:12,351
where you put those things that matter.

589
00:35:12,852 --> 00:35:14,252
That's how you tell a story using pacing

590
00:35:14,292 --> 00:35:15,192
as your fundamental unit.

