700
00:43:25,834 --> 00:43:29,137
And that's because the game was entirely playable at my level without a horse.

701
00:43:29,577 --> 00:43:30,998
It was just slightly easier with one.

702
00:43:31,298 --> 00:43:35,962
And I was privileged enough to have five pounds but not five hours, so I made that choice.

703
00:43:36,022 --> 00:43:41,366
So I want to be clear that I don't think that monetization is in itself a bad thing or always corrupt.

704
00:43:41,847 --> 00:43:43,308
Elder Scrolls stayed classy, I thought.

705
00:43:44,069 --> 00:43:47,371
So I believe that you can design games ethically and make money,

706
00:43:47,831 --> 00:43:50,013
but a clever friend of mine once said,

707
00:43:50,613 --> 00:43:52,535
yes, but maybe not as much money.

708
00:43:53,015 --> 00:43:55,077
And I'm not going to stand up here and characterize

709
00:43:55,137 --> 00:43:57,318
wanting to make money as absolutely morally corrupt.

710
00:43:57,599 --> 00:43:59,400
I too like being able to pay my bills.

711
00:43:59,840 --> 00:44:02,262
But I do think it's important to say that many of the designers

712
00:44:02,382 --> 00:44:04,864
making games that do monetization and free-to-play

713
00:44:04,924 --> 00:44:07,906
and good design ethically have done so knowing

714
00:44:07,986 --> 00:44:11,009
that they could be squeezing more money out of their players,

715
00:44:11,729 --> 00:44:12,350
at least for a while.

716
00:44:13,453 --> 00:44:14,474
But the thing is they don't.

717
00:44:14,994 --> 00:44:18,254
And that is not an inefficiency or naivete,

718
00:44:18,635 --> 00:44:20,475
but a deliberate design choice.

719
00:44:20,835 --> 00:44:23,236
Exploitative design is a choice too.

720
00:44:23,316 --> 00:44:24,456
It isn't inevitable.

721
00:44:24,896 --> 00:44:27,617
And we are abdicating our moral responsibility

722
00:44:27,777 --> 00:44:30,897
as artists and human beings if we pretend that it is.

723
00:44:31,277 --> 00:44:33,318
When we use that excuse as designers,

724
00:44:33,598 --> 00:44:36,899
we are in some small but real ways training our players

725
00:44:37,199 --> 00:44:39,979
to accept broken and disrespectful systems

726
00:44:40,019 --> 00:44:41,600
and ideas by normalizing them.

727
00:44:42,100 --> 00:44:46,166
What we train our players to do in games leaks out into the real world.

728
00:44:46,927 --> 00:44:50,312
So there is a porous boundary between games and the world in which we live.

729
00:44:50,732 --> 00:44:55,399
Game design and the thinking that comes with it, all of these things, are already influencing

730
00:44:55,419 --> 00:44:55,740
the world.

731
00:44:56,120 --> 00:44:57,022
But unfortunately...

732
00:44:57,022 --> 00:45:02,046
Unfortunately, what is out there is the most banal game design at its most exploitative

733
00:45:02,087 --> 00:45:09,053
and capitalistic, reinforcing the worst practices, all sanctified on the holy altar of optimization.

734
00:45:09,494 --> 00:45:14,399
But I do also genuinely believe that we are at a moment that is full of the possibility

735
00:45:14,419 --> 00:45:14,859
of change.

736
00:45:16,244 --> 00:45:21,270
A lot of people, so many people that would have not had the vocabulary to talk about

737
00:45:21,410 --> 00:45:26,096
systems and institutions actually do these days because they play games.

738
00:45:26,536 --> 00:45:30,941
When we talk about a class being nerfed or overpowered, we're actually just talking about

739
00:45:30,981 --> 00:45:31,362
privilege.

740
00:45:32,062 --> 00:45:37,025
And so as designers and players, we are in this space of unprecedented literacy

741
00:45:37,446 --> 00:45:39,247
about systems thinking and design.

742
00:45:39,647 --> 00:45:44,510
These are the tools that helped me understand my own feelings of anger and helplessness

743
00:45:44,850 --> 00:45:46,211
sitting in that passport office.

744
00:45:46,812 --> 00:45:49,413
And these are the tools that I use to take that helplessness

745
00:45:49,854 --> 00:45:54,637
and turn it into a conversation with you in this room and outside of it.

746
00:45:55,097 --> 00:45:57,618
Games can help us understand the world and each other.

747
00:45:58,039 --> 00:46:01,341
And as designers of games and narratives and art.

748
00:46:01,841 --> 00:46:09,111
We have so many opportunities to completely, radically reimagine how systems could work.

749
00:46:09,732 --> 00:46:16,982
Democracies and dictatorships, bureaucracies and social and cultural institutions, these are hard to change.

750
00:46:17,402 --> 00:46:21,725
And I'm really not here to suggest that games can change the world all on their own,

751
00:46:22,065 --> 00:46:25,428
but they can change how a person feels and thinks.

752
00:46:26,088 --> 00:46:27,629
We wouldn't be here otherwise.

753
00:46:28,250 --> 00:46:33,653
And games are a space, a creative, open, and as yet largely undefined space.

754
00:46:33,974 --> 00:46:40,498
Where we can experiment with different ways of being, interacting, participating, collaborating and competing.

755
00:46:41,098 --> 00:46:50,424
So that when history asks us, what did you do in this moment, at this particular time and place, with all the possibilities available to you?

756
00:46:51,064 --> 00:46:54,506
I don't want my answer to be, I made a slot machine.

757
00:46:55,367 --> 00:46:55,767
Thank you.

758
00:47:09,092 --> 00:47:10,353
Thank you very much indeed, Meg.

759
00:47:11,654 --> 00:47:16,938
For our penultimate micro-talk of this evening, please welcome Brie Code.

760
00:47:25,825 --> 00:47:32,891
So, I find, I love video games, but my friends find video games boring.

761
00:47:33,371 --> 00:47:38,115
Cultural reasons aside, I think there's an underlying physiological reason why they find

762
00:47:38,175 --> 00:47:38,776
games boring.

763
00:47:39,422 --> 00:47:41,684
I think it has something to do with stress reactions.

764
00:47:44,386 --> 00:47:48,288
When you're playing a video game and lots of things are flashing on screen and there's

765
00:47:48,349 --> 00:47:52,131
danger and it's shocking and it's fun, that's a fight or flight reaction.

766
00:47:52,752 --> 00:47:56,875
Your sympathetic nervous system kicks in and adrenaline is released through your system

767
00:47:56,915 --> 00:47:57,855
followed by dopamine.

768
00:48:00,212 --> 00:48:04,375
And if you enjoy games like this, it's probably because adrenaline and dopamine are really fun.

769
00:48:04,955 --> 00:48:09,038
Adrenaline makes your pupils dilate, your heart beats faster, like mine is right now,

770
00:48:09,539 --> 00:48:12,621
your airways open up and you feel exhilarated, you feel alive.

771
00:48:16,383 --> 00:48:21,707
But I think my friends find games boring not only because they aren't interested in more stories about white men,

772
00:48:22,147 --> 00:48:24,449
and not only because they don't know how the controls work,

773
00:48:24,989 --> 00:48:27,091
but also because they don't get an adrenaline high.

774
00:48:27,591 --> 00:48:29,152
They have a different reaction to stress.

775
00:48:32,913 --> 00:48:37,037
This is my cousin, Christina. Maybe a couple of you remember her from a thing I wrote earlier

776
00:48:37,137 --> 00:48:41,701
called Video Games are Boring. Christina is one of my friends who finds video games boring.

777
00:48:42,441 --> 00:48:47,986
What she loves instead are contemporary feminist art, vegan food, and longboarding with her

778
00:48:48,066 --> 00:48:53,771
friends. A few years ago, Christina was given a PS3 and I recommended that she play my favorite

779
00:48:53,812 --> 00:48:58,636
game, Skyrim. I didn't hear from her for three weeks, and I thought she didn't play it.

780
00:48:59,390 --> 00:49:03,677
Then one evening she called me crying because she had accidentally killed Lydia.

781
00:49:05,860 --> 00:49:07,903
Christina finds video games boring.

782
00:49:08,398 --> 00:49:09,659
But she loved Skyrim.

783
00:49:10,139 --> 00:49:15,062
She isn't interested in medieval warfare or swords or dragons whatsoever, and she found

784
00:49:15,082 --> 00:49:15,903
the controls hard.

785
00:49:16,503 --> 00:49:18,964
But she loved Skyrim because she loved the characters.

786
00:49:19,585 --> 00:49:22,327
Christina doesn't like being shocked, but she loves taking care.

787
00:49:22,867 --> 00:49:26,749
She loved creating her character, doing quests for other characters, joining guilds, and

788
00:49:26,789 --> 00:49:28,530
bringing Lydia along on her adventures.

789
00:49:29,411 --> 00:49:32,773
She said to me that it turns out that it wasn't that she didn't like video games.

790
00:49:33,393 --> 00:49:35,255
It was that she didn't know what video games could be.

791
00:49:37,453 --> 00:49:41,337
Christina doesn't like adrenaline, but with Skyrim there's something similar that was

792
00:49:41,397 --> 00:49:42,578
probably going on with her.

793
00:49:43,279 --> 00:49:44,720
It's called tend and befriend.

794
00:49:45,381 --> 00:49:50,405
Like fight or flight, tend and befriend is an automatic physiological reaction to stress.

795
00:49:53,413 --> 00:49:57,459
If you experience tendon bifurcation, your body releases oxytocin or vasopressin when

796
00:49:57,479 --> 00:49:59,262
you are threatened, followed by opioids.

797
00:49:59,943 --> 00:50:03,429
This calms your sympathetic nervous system so you don't get the flood of adrenaline.

798
00:50:04,010 --> 00:50:07,736
Instead of wanting to fight or to flee, you stay relatively calm but aware.

799
00:50:09,438 --> 00:50:12,981
Your pupils dilate, you become fearless, and you are less sensitive to pain.

800
00:50:13,661 --> 00:50:17,825
You instinctively want to protect your loved ones and to seek out your allies and form

801
00:50:17,865 --> 00:50:18,586
new alliances.

802
00:50:19,406 --> 00:50:23,810
Oxytocin intensifies social feelings, and opioids feel really, really good.

803
00:50:25,472 --> 00:50:28,934
And the oxytocin opioid thing isn't limited to threatening interactions.

804
00:50:29,615 --> 00:50:34,159
It's also there when you touch or even think about someone you love, when you play fetch

805
00:50:34,199 --> 00:50:37,121
with your dog, or even when you exclude someone you don't like.

806
00:50:41,618 --> 00:50:43,600
When I read about Tendon Befriend, I was like,

807
00:50:43,680 --> 00:50:45,521
shit, this is how I usually react to stress.

808
00:50:46,482 --> 00:50:47,663
Most of my friends do too.

809
00:50:48,183 --> 00:50:50,325
Most women and many men have this reaction,

810
00:50:50,365 --> 00:50:51,586
but have you heard of it before?

811
00:50:52,106 --> 00:50:54,208
Maybe not, because it's barely been studied.

812
00:50:54,688 --> 00:50:56,049
It's barely been discussed.

813
00:50:56,990 --> 00:51:00,132
It's barely just been identified at UCLA in 2000.

814
00:51:00,793 --> 00:51:03,475
Like much other research, most stress research

815
00:51:03,515 --> 00:51:05,737
had been done with men and with male animals.

816
00:51:06,457 --> 00:51:08,659
Researchers traditionally prefer bodies

817
00:51:08,719 --> 00:51:09,820
that don't menstruate.

818
00:51:10,800 --> 00:51:13,521
Maybe everything we know about ourselves is wrong.

819
00:51:14,561 --> 00:51:17,462
We see these kinds of mistakes also in the design of cities,

820
00:51:17,902 --> 00:51:20,003
the design of airbags, etc.

821
00:51:20,063 --> 00:51:24,044
And a games researcher once told me that his team also doesn't try to study women

822
00:51:24,064 --> 00:51:26,584
because, in his words, you can't predict women.

823
00:51:27,725 --> 00:51:30,085
This is really fucking boring.

824
00:51:30,105 --> 00:51:35,327
A woman I very much respect, though, told me that you can't change the world,

825
00:51:35,387 --> 00:51:37,207
but you can make your little corner of it better.

826
00:51:37,973 --> 00:51:40,755
I'm bored of patriarchy and its lasting effects on my life,

827
00:51:40,795 --> 00:51:44,896
but I'm very interested in looking at the gaps in research and in design and fixing them.

828
00:51:45,536 --> 00:51:45,917
Are you?

829
00:51:47,217 --> 00:51:48,397
What is game design missing?

830
00:51:48,437 --> 00:51:51,379
I ask this question not just in terms of cultural elements,

831
00:51:51,419 --> 00:51:53,820
such as diverse protagonists, which are very important,

832
00:51:54,260 --> 00:51:57,381
but also in terms of satisfying game mechanics and game systems.

833
00:51:57,921 --> 00:52:02,163
I ask in terms of what we take for granted about play styles, player motivation, etc.,

834
00:52:02,183 --> 00:52:07,105
but also about adrenaline, dopamine, oxytocin, opioids, and other reward systems.

835
00:52:07,726 --> 00:52:10,193
about what it takes to induce a flow state in the player.

836
00:52:10,674 --> 00:52:11,857
Who designed these rules?

837
00:52:12,238 --> 00:52:13,742
What players are we studying?

838
00:52:14,525 --> 00:52:16,029
And who should we be talking to?

839
00:52:18,150 --> 00:52:22,895
And I want to be clear that care is not weak or simple or cute and doesn't only belong

840
00:52:22,935 --> 00:52:24,196
in simple or cute games.

841
00:52:24,757 --> 00:52:28,922
Caring for your chosen loved ones and the formation of new alliances are sophisticated

842
00:52:29,062 --> 00:52:31,304
actions and can be acts of warfare.

843
00:52:31,965 --> 00:52:34,828
Care is stronger and more interesting than brutality or fear.

844
00:52:35,289 --> 00:52:36,590
There's a lot to be explored here.

845
00:52:36,670 --> 00:52:37,771
I encourage you to question.

846
00:52:38,332 --> 00:52:41,856
What you take for granted about yourself and other people and about games.

847
00:52:42,496 --> 00:52:48,402
And if you are underrepresented, look into your heart because maybe everything we know is wrong, but you are right.

848
00:52:50,144 --> 00:52:50,445
Thank you.

849
00:53:06,422 --> 00:53:12,425
Uh, Kat, Bree, Christine, do you want to come up here with me? We'll get started on our last

850
00:53:12,866 --> 00:53:18,629
micro talk of the day, uh, which was crowdsourced online from among our networks of friends

851
00:53:18,969 --> 00:53:24,252
and from you, the micro talks community. We asked for messages of resistance and hope

852
00:53:25,012 --> 00:53:26,433
and here's what people said.

853
00:53:32,835 --> 00:53:37,159
In times of great doubt, you might hear again the voices snickering at your heels.

854
00:53:37,779 --> 00:53:39,140
Games are a waste of time.

855
00:53:39,861 --> 00:53:44,884
But now, like every work of art, games allow us to see further and live a thousand lives.

856
00:53:49,768 --> 00:53:54,211
Be soft and open to sharing knowledge with those around you, especially the younger folk.

857
00:53:54,772 --> 00:53:58,855
Your wisdom will help fortify their success towards progression and excellence in their fields.

858
00:54:04,139 --> 00:54:07,822
It is quite possible to create dramatic internal change with language and symbol.

859
00:54:08,263 --> 00:54:12,087
This change then reverberates into the outer world, reshaping and reorganizing it.

860
00:54:12,527 --> 00:54:13,268
You can use this.

861
00:54:21,457 --> 00:54:26,081
In good times and in bad, the desire to create and to play unites us as one human family.

862
00:54:31,688 --> 00:54:33,310
Every game is political.

863
00:54:33,710 --> 00:54:37,734
Keep making them boldly, with your head and your heart.

864
00:54:38,115 --> 00:54:42,639
There is nothing a tyrant hates more than the sounds of laughter and of play.

865
00:54:48,526 --> 00:54:53,451
The more you tighten your grip, the more the stars distance will slip through your fingers.

866
00:55:00,076 --> 00:55:04,401
Kodum says, I went into 2016 being seen as one gender.

867
00:55:04,982 --> 00:55:06,984
Now I'm universally known as another.

868
00:55:07,905 --> 00:55:10,449
Trans people in games, you've done so much.

869
00:55:10,929 --> 00:55:11,250
Thank you.

870
00:55:17,167 --> 00:55:19,828
When life is becoming increasingly harder on the outside,

871
00:55:20,048 --> 00:55:23,088
don't forget to cherish your inner creamy caramel filling.

872
00:55:23,568 --> 00:55:25,009
Take a break from your work often

873
00:55:25,209 --> 00:55:27,029
and spend your time with good people,

874
00:55:27,149 --> 00:55:28,569
good food, and warm blankets.

875
00:55:29,169 --> 00:55:32,190
Make your games to show others what the world could be like,

876
00:55:32,410 --> 00:55:33,090
not as it is.

877
00:55:39,391 --> 00:55:41,312
In my mind, a lot of the bad things

878
00:55:41,332 --> 00:55:44,032
we currently have in our world don't stand a chance

879
00:55:44,132 --> 00:55:45,613
in light of what we are capable of

880
00:55:45,653 --> 00:55:46,653
when we work together.

881
00:55:47,728 --> 00:55:49,790
We're stewarding so much influence here,

882
00:55:49,810 --> 00:55:52,912
and I'm inspired by you all who live out

883
00:55:53,513 --> 00:55:54,453
the fullness of that.

884
00:55:59,858 --> 00:56:00,798
Be compassionate.

885
00:56:01,439 --> 00:56:04,642
The growing gap between rich and poor is the root problem.

886
00:56:05,302 --> 00:56:08,024
Resist racism, resist anti-immigration,

887
00:56:08,164 --> 00:56:09,786
and fight for everyone's right to work.

888
00:56:16,560 --> 00:56:19,341
Be generous in prosperity and thankful in adversity.

889
00:56:19,681 --> 00:56:21,822
Be worthy of the trust of thy neighbor,

890
00:56:22,142 --> 00:56:24,723
and look upon them with a bright and friendly face.

891
00:56:25,303 --> 00:56:28,144
Be a treasure to the poor, an admonisher to the rich,

892
00:56:28,624 --> 00:56:30,164
an answer to the cry of the needy.

893
00:56:30,605 --> 00:56:33,686
Be as a lamp unto them that walk in darkness,

894
00:56:34,226 --> 00:56:36,987
a joy to the sorrowful, a sea for the thirsty,

895
00:56:37,347 --> 00:56:40,468
a haven for the distressed, an upholder and defender

896
00:56:40,808 --> 00:56:41,848
of the victim of oppression.

897
00:56:47,185 --> 00:56:48,406
Never surrender the dream.

898
00:56:55,491 --> 00:56:58,554
These words are in honor of everyone who couldn't be with us

899
00:56:58,834 --> 00:57:01,436
at GDC this year for every kind of reason.

900
00:57:02,017 --> 00:57:05,740
Thanks to everyone who sent in their thoughts for us to share here this

901
00:57:05,860 --> 00:57:06,100
evening.

902
00:57:07,350 --> 00:57:10,176
Have a wonderful rest of GDC everyone.

903
00:57:10,477 --> 00:57:12,281
Take care of yourselves and each other.

904
00:57:12,641 --> 00:57:14,285
Thanks again to all of our speakers

905
00:57:14,706 --> 00:57:15,728
and to thank you for coming.

906
00:57:16,369 --> 00:57:17,391
Have a wonderful evening.

